sta rap and law breaking, Russell-Brown challenges the conventional wisdom of criminology. Underground Codes delves into understudied topics such as victimization rates for Native Americans-among the highest of any racial group-and how racial profiling affects the day-to-day lives of people of color. Innovative, well-researched and meticulously documented, Underground Codes makes a case for greater public involvement in the debate over law enforcement-and our own language-that must be heard if we are to begin to have a productive national conversation about crime and race.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aCrime and racezUnited States. 0aCrime and race. 0aDiscrimination in criminal justice administrationzUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in criminal justice administration. 0aDiscrimination in law enforcementzUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in law enforcement. 0aMinoritieszUnited States. 0aMinorities. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aamerican.  acodes.  aenforcement.  aexamination.  ainfluence.  alaw.  amyths.  apolicy.  apowerful.  apublic.  aracial.  athat.  aunspoken.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814769249423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814769249/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK